, Kolhapur is placed on the Panchaganga River. Kolhapur is 230 kilometres from Pune and has a long history connected to the Marathas. Kolhapur is famous for its necklaces and sandals, which are popular worldwide. Kolhasur, a demon destroyed by Goddess Mahalakshmi, is the mythological figure from whom Kolhapur derives its name. In honour of Goddess Mahalakshmi, the well-known Mahalakshmi temple is located here. The food, jewellery, and sandals of Kolhapur are famous throughout India. It is a place that welcomes tourists and with easily accessible to hotels and restaurants. Here refers to some of the best tourist places in Kolhapur, which tourists should never miss. 1. Shree Mahalaxmi Mandir The Shree Mahalaxmi Mandir, constructed in the seventh century under the time of the Chalukyas, is one of the most tranquil locations to visit in Kolhapur. It is a famous Hindu pilgrimage site where devotees from various areas travel to seek blessings. The Hindu religion honours Mahalakshmi, sometimes referred to as Goddess Ambabai. One of India's most significant pilgrimage sites is the temple, and the distance between the temple and the city's Central Bus Depot is roughly 5 kilometres. Location: Kolhapur, Maharashtra 416012, Mahadwar Road, B Ward, and C Ward Ideal Time: June through February Hours: 5:00 a.m. to 11:00 a.m. and 4:00 p.m. to 8:00 p.m. 2. New Palace Understand Chatrapati Shahu Maharaj's way of life by visiting the New Palace, which was constructed on the Bhavani Mandap Kasaba Bawada Road. New Palace is one of the best tourist destinations in Kolhapur if you love history because it displays the ancient artefacts and valuables of the Maharaja and his family. The first floor has been converted into a museum, with the bottom floor remaining off-limits to visitors. The Palace is made of black polished stone and has an unusual architectural design. Best Period: June through February Time: 9:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. Price: INR 18 per individual 3. Panhala Fort The Panhala Fort, the enormous Fort in the Deccan area, is placed close to Kolhapur City. The fact that it connects Maharashtra to the Arabian Sea via Bijapur fascinates anybody who enjoys learning about history and geography. The Indo-Islamic architecture adds to the Fort's presentation of numerous themes, bastions, and other artefacts from many royal families. The Maratha empire formerly developed here, and visitors can also get a bird's-eye view of the surrounding area from the top of the hill. Best Period: June through February Hours: Always open 4. Radhanagari Wildlife Sanctuary The Radhanagari Wildlife Sanctuary is a must-see attraction in Kolhapur since it is the ideal location for visitors. They may see different species of birds, reptiles, and several types of animals here. The Sanctuary is near Radhanagari, which is crossed by the Bhogavati, Dudhganga, Tulsi, Kalama, and Dirba rivers. This area is home to a unique variety of plants and wildlife, including sambar, gigantic squirrels, spotted deer, mouse deer, and sloth bears in large numbers. Best Time: June to September during the monsoon season. Time: 7:00 am to 2:30 pm The price per person begins at INR 120. 5. Shri Binkhambi Ganesh Mandir The Shri Binkhambi Ganesh Mandir, constructed to glorify Lord Ganesh, is one of Kolhapur's most peaceful tourist destinations. As the temple is formed out of a single pillar, the temple's architecture is highly intriguing, drawing visitors from all over the world. One of the top tourist attractions in Kolhapur is this location where visitors may worship Lord Ganesha for his blessing. Best Period: From June to February Time: Open from 5:30 a.m. to 8:00 p.m. 6. Kopeshwar Temple Kopeshwar Temple was erected on the banks of the river Krishna in the 12th century to receive Lord Shiva's blessings. The temple is elaborately constructed, and its beautiful pillars are decorated with representations of gods and goddesses. There are also idols of a few other gods, including Vishnu, the Nandi bull, and several others. Due to its outstanding construction, the temple draws not only worshippers but also history lovers. Best Period: Monsoon season, from June through September. Times are from 7:00 am to 11:30 am and from 4:00 pm to 8:00 pm. 7. Sagareshwar Deer Sanctuary The Sagareshwar Deer Sanctuary, a protected area in the Kolhapur district, is an additional attraction among the many sites to see in Kolhapur. This area has 11 square kilometres of artificial forest, and there is wildlife. Whether you're looking for an unusual variety of plants or animals, this is the ideal location. Best Period: June through February Time: 8:00 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. 8. Rankala Lake Rankala Lake, a well-known attraction in the area, is one of the many tourist destinations in Kolhapur. The lake, which combines Rajghat and Maraghat, was constructed by "Shri Chhatrapati Shahu Maharaj", the king of Kolhapur. It spreads across an area of 107 hectares, and the sights it offers are almost unimaginable. The lake is thought to have been constructed by the Maharaj and has a long history going back to ancient times. Rankala Lake is the ideal location for you if you're seeking a place to relax and calm your mind. Best Period: June through September Time: Always open 9. Jyotiba Temple One of the most stunning spots in Kolhapur is the "Jyotiba Temple," which is in the middle of the city. The temple is filled with gulal when gulal or rings are delivered to God as a sign of affection. Over 3124 feet above sea level, where the temple is located, you may gaze at the town's stunning view. The God named "Jyotiba", who resides in the temple is thought to be a combination of three divine gods. According to the locals, one should visit the temple after asking the Goddess "Mahalaxmi" for her blessing. Best Period: June through February Time: 6:00 a.m. to 10:30 p.m. 10. Siddhagiri Gramjivan Museum Kaneri's Siddhagiri Gramjivan Museum is the best option for visitors. It is also known as the Kaneri Math and contains a stunning Shiva temple inside the Shri Kshetra Siddhagiri Math. A visitor may see figures made of wax and cement at this museum that reflects a villager's way of life. Throughout its entire 7-acre area, the museum is encircled by beautiful nature on all sides. Best Period: June through February Time: 9:00 a.m. to 6:00 p.m. 11. Gaganbawada Gaganbawada, also known as the Sahyadris, is a town on the Western Ghats that is 55 kilometres from Kolhapur. The undeveloped hill village is known for its nearby attractions, including the Gagangad Fort, Bhuibavda Ghat, and Karul Ghat; the village is featured in several Bollywood films. Best times to go: August until April. 12. Ramtirth Waterfall Ramtirth waterfall, a natural waterfall famous for its incomparable tranquillity and stunning surroundings, flows down on the banks of the River Hiranyakeshi in Ajara Taluka, Kolhapur. The area is mainly visited for daytime picnics and to escape the city's noise. There are also several temples in the neighbourhood, which are always filled with visitors. 13. Dream World Water Park The Dream World Water Park is a great place to slide down into the water and play with the colourful water balloons. Up to 8 slides in various colours are available to play about in the water and enjoy yourself with your family. In addition, there is a dazzling deep pool and a shallow side of the pool where you may rest. Additionally, a cafe is constructed inside the park where you may enjoy delicious treats. Best Period: May through October Hours are 10:00 am to 9:00 pm. Price: INR 500 per person and above. 14. Kalamba Lake The Kalamba Lake covers 63 hectares and is one of the most impressive spots to see in Kolhapur. And this is the main water supply for the entire city. The lake's base is Katyayni hill, and the city is close to the lake's smooth water flow. During the winter, many migrating birds arrive at this lake, increasing its attractiveness. Best Period: June through September Hours: Always acce